---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import RelatedConnectors from "../../components/RelatedConnectors.astro";
import { connectors } from "../../data/connectors";

// Every connector that can be used as a destination in Datanika's load
// layer. Computed from the data file: a connector is a destination if its
// direction is not "source" (i.e. "destination" or "both"). This includes
// all databases (Postgres, MySQL, SQLite, etc.), all cloud warehouses, and
// DuckDB. If a new destination connector is added to connectors.ts, it
// shows up here automatically — no hardcoded list to maintain.
const destinationConnectors = connectors.filter((c) => c.direction !== "source");
---

<DocsLayout title="Architecture" description="Technical overview of Datanika's architecture, tech stack, data flow, and security model.">
  <h1>Architecture</h1>
  <p class="text-lg text-slate-400">How Datanika works under the hood — for technical evaluators and self-hosting users.</p>

  <h2>System Overview</h2>
  <p>Datanika is a multi-tenant data pipeline platform built with:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>dlt</strong> (data load tool) — Extract + Load from 27 sources to 11 destinations</li>
    <li><strong>dbt-core</strong> — Transform (SQL models, tests, snapshots, packages)</li>
    <li><strong>Reflex</strong> — Full-stack Python UI (compiles to React, no separate JS codebase)</li>
    <li><strong>PostgreSQL</strong> — Application database + pipeline metadata</li>
    <li><strong>Redis</strong> — Celery broker + APScheduler job store + session cache</li>
    <li><strong>Celery</strong> — Async task execution for pipeline and transformation runs</li>
    <li><strong>APScheduler</strong> — Cron-based scheduling with PostgreSQL persistence</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Architecture Diagram</h2>
  <pre><code set:html={`┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    Reflex Frontend (React)                    │
│  Sources  │  Pipelines  │  Transforms  │  Scheduling  │  Runs│
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                  Reflex Backend (Starlette)                   │
│  Auth & RBAC  │  REST API v1  │  Pipeline Engine  │ Scheduler│
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  PostgreSQL            │  Redis             │  Celery Workers │
│  • App metadata        │  • Task broker     │  • dlt extract  │
│  • Pipeline data       │  • Job store       │  • dlt load     │
│  • Tenant isolation    │  • Session cache   │  • dbt transform│
│  • Audit logs          │  • Rate limiting   │  • dbt test     │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘`} /></pre>

  <h2>Data Flow</h2>
  <h3>1. Extract + Load</h3>
  <p>User configures a source connection and a destination connection, then creates an upload. When triggered (manually or by schedule), a Celery task runs dlt to extract data from the source and load it into the destination schema. dlt handles schema mapping, type conversion, and incremental loading automatically.</p>

  <h3>2. Transform</h3>
  <p>User writes SQL models in Datanika's built-in editor. Models are stored as <code>.sql</code> files in per-tenant dbt projects at <code>dbt_projects/tenant_{'{org_id}'}/</code>. When a pipeline runs, dbt-core compiles and executes the models against the destination warehouse.</p>

  <h3>3. Orchestrate</h3>
  <p>Schedules are managed by APScheduler with a PostgreSQL job store (persistent across restarts). Each schedule triggers an upload, transformation, or pipeline on a cron expression. Dependencies form a DAG — downstream tasks wait for upstream completion before executing.</p>

  <h2>Multi-Tenancy</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>All tables in the <code>public</code> schema with <code>org_id</code> column filtering (no schema-per-tenant)</li>
    <li><code>TenantMixin</code> base class ensures every query is scoped to the current organization</li>
    <li>Per-tenant dbt projects at <code>dbt_projects/tenant_{'{org_id}'}/</code> — fully isolated</li>
    <li>Data destination schemas are user-configured per pipeline (not hardcoded)</li>
    <li>5 tenant isolation security tests verify cross-tenant access is impossible</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Authentication &amp; Authorization</h2>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Layer</th><th>Technology</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Password auth</td><td>bcrypt</td><td>Direct hashing, no passlib dependency</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tokens</td><td>JWT (python-jose)</td><td>Stateless auth with configurable expiry</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Social login</td><td>OAuth2</td><td>Google + GitHub via Starlette routes</td></tr>
      <tr><td>SSO</td><td>SAML + OIDC</td><td>Enterprise plan — per-org configuration</td></tr>
      <tr><td>API auth</td><td>Bearer tokens</td><td>API keys with scopes, rate limiting per plan</td></tr>
      <tr><td>RBAC</td><td>4 roles</td><td>Owner, Admin, Editor, Viewer — enforced in UI state layer</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Plugin Architecture</h2>
  <p>Datanika uses a hooks-based plugin system to keep the open-source core clean while supporting commercial features:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Core</strong> (<code>datanika/</code>) — Open-source under AGPL-3.0. Contains all features except billing.</li>
    <li><strong>Cloud plugin</strong> (<code>datanika-cloud/</code>) — Adds subscription billing (Paddle), quota enforcement, and usage metering.</li>
    <li><strong>Hooks system</strong> (<code>hooks.py</code>) — Core emits events (e.g., <code>connection.before_create</code>, <code>run.upload_completed</code>), plugins subscribe with handlers.</li>
    <li>Activated by setting <code>DATANIKA_EDITION=cloud</code>. Without it, the core runs with no limits.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>REST API</h2>
  <p>Full programmatic access via REST API v1:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>CRUD for connections, uploads, pipelines, transformations, schedules, notification channels</li>
    <li>Trigger endpoints for running uploads, pipelines, and transformations</li>
    <li>OpenAPI 3.0 spec at <code>/api/v1/openapi.json</code></li>
    <li>Interactive Swagger UI at <code>/api/v1/docs</code></li>
    <li>Rate limiting: Free 30rpm, Pro 120rpm, Enterprise 300rpm</li>
  </ul>
  <p>See <a href="/api/reference">API Reference</a> for full endpoint documentation.</p>

  <h2>Security Model</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Encryption at rest</strong> — All connection credentials encrypted with Fernet symmetric encryption</li>
    <li><strong>Webhook verification</strong> — HMAC-verified Paddle webhooks</li>
    <li><strong>CAPTCHA</strong> — reCAPTCHA v3 on login/signup (configurable, disabled when keys empty)</li>
    <li><strong>Audit logging</strong> — All mutating actions logged with user, timestamp, resource type, and action</li>
    <li><strong>Input validation</strong> — 24 input validation security tests</li>
    <li><strong>Injection protection</strong> — 11 injection security tests (SQL, XSS, command)</li>
    <li><strong>Auth attack protection</strong> — 19 auth attack security tests</li>
    <li><strong>Path traversal protection</strong> — 8 path traversal security tests</li>
    <li><strong>73 security tests total</strong> covering OWASP top 10 categories</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Technology Stack</h2>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Component</th><th>Technology</th><th>Why</th></tr></thead>
